Ending 2022 making racists mad about my ESSENCE article being featured on @mapsnews feels very fitting. I wanted to be more fearless and more honest in the new year and there is nothing I can think of more fearless and honest than Toni Morrison in this interview. People who have always had things catered to them will always convulse when something is finally not about them. How ODD that Black women want to talk about their very personal experience with 🍄 — how very odd to not include us, too! And somehow EYE become the person stoking the fire of division, by simply telling a story. 💡 DID YOU KNOW that it’s okay to tell stories that don’t include everyone??? The best stories are often about someone different than you’s experience. Cue Solange “F.U.B.U.”

Sometimes I hear words in my head and I call them messages. 🌺 I know, I know. Do with that information what you will, make whatever assumptions you need to. The fact is, I don’t want to fight, strangle, control, judge any parts of myself anymore. I want to question them. “Why are you here? What purpose do you serve? From whence do you come?” So here’s some for you: What are you telling yourself about yourself? Any why do you believe that? Pull at the thread a little. 🧵
Okay, okay, okay, I got a new gig, big whoop 🎈the REAL accomplishment is how ~on brand~ the vibes are. 🌈

Eating dinner without my phone in hand and I thought about why it was so uncomfortable for me to simply eat my food with no other activity to do. My brain wanted something else to do while eating, and then it whispered “you need to be eating with friends, bitch.” So I just wrote what I was thinking while eating. 🧠 But in addition, I feel like I rarely get to do just one brain activity at a time. Even this morning. I was walking to my desk and eating a banana. Why couldn’t I just wait to sit at my desk and THEN eat the banana? Has capitalism instilled the idea of efficiency so much into our lives that we try to shave off seconds of a task so we can use that time to work more? We need more community and we need to give our brains a break from multitasking. Here is my disorganized TedTalk. Thank you.

I often think about the world ending (because it is) and every now and then I think of the other paths my life could’ve taken (there were many, many others). And when I think of these things, I try to snap myself back into the present. “The world hasn’t ended yet, you ding dong,” I think. “And if this is the life you get to experience while the world is still turning, how wonderfully lucky.” There will always be something. Things will always be happening. But this is what I get to have. This — glorious, messy, human, but most of all tangible — this. So much of my life is /has been unknown, so I fill in the gaps with my imagination. But this is real. I wake up and it’s there. In whatever state it’s in, it’s there. (I don’t recommend PMS-ing on Valentine’s Day, I am ashambles over here looking at you guys, looking at old pictures of my baby, JUST A HOT MESS BALL OF EMOTIONSSSSS!!!!!)

A chaotic WIP…I think. Maybe it’s done. Maybe not. 🌀 In true aries fashion, I never know when to stop. Are you an “add more” person or a “this is fine” kinda guy/gal? Writing, I learned that the art is in the edit, but painting is different. I think that’s why I like it so much. I chose a career filled with edits, but I don’t need to when I paint. No CTRL+ ALT+DELETE here. What’s there is there and I can go over what’s there with more paint, but I don’t ever remove it. I just build on top of it and there’ll always a reminder of what was if you look close enough.

POV: you’re a mom. It’s a quiet Sunday morning and your body is sleeping hard, getting the rest it’s needed all week. All of a sudden, the sound of one foot and then the other hits the floor. You slowly blink and try to rub the crusty eye boogers from your eyes. There’s a pause. No sound. Maybe you misheard? Then, those two little feet start padding over, the sound getting louder as they get closer. The child you made enters your bedroom and climbs into bed with you. You adjust more than you should have to for someone with a body so tiny. Your daughter has just woken up and started your day for you. Wait, is the dog in here, too? It’s a question you don’t need answered. Everything is a blur. A messy, sleep deprived, lovely blur.

True Life: I Just Be Doing Stuff 🎨 I found an old dusty painting in a gorgeous gilded frame that had been damaged. I filled in the chips with paint and painted over the old one. I get that I’m not a classically trained artist (is that a thing?) but I don’t paint to be good. I paint to be free.

If you think about it, woman crush Wednesday was one of the first ways we, as a society, held regular and dedicated time to praise the women in our lives. AND AS WE KNOW, relative to all we do, we receive the least praise. The ONLY way to combat this systemic disregard (to our detriment) is with systemic acknowledgment (to our benefit). And in this essay I will detail the several reasons we should bring it back as regular practice, as well as my belief on what doing so would mean for our culture — nay, our world. 🫡 By the way, my #wcw is me! 💕😘💋
You can be human. You can be perfect. You cannot be both.

Do you have a praise kink *or* do you just have anxiety and if people aren’t telling you how wonderful you are all the time (even if you already know you’re wonderful!!!), you get worried they don’t see/value/adore you — AND IF THEY DON’T SEE/VALUE/ADORE YOU, whatever the nature of your relationship, your anxiety tells you ⚠️ DANGER ⚠️ RUN FOR THE MF HILLS, you are not on solid ground! Microdosing freedom 🎨 Ya girl has been going through it, over it, under it and around it — BUT AND STILL — I’m here. And what’s more is I’m here AS MYSELF. Fully Audrey Patricia Williams. And I love me some me. ❤️ And to be anything less than myself would be an insult to everything and everyone who has helped me become me. How dare I deny me me???? Sheeeeeiiit.

Hey, so me and my dying plant have a question for you: when you make decisions, do you make them from the inside out or the outside in? Lately, I’ve found myself making decisions based on “what just makes sense” — but what I never stopped to question was WHOSE SENSE? To whomst did the “sense” governing my life belong? The only person your decision has to make 100% sense to is yourself (okay, that’s hyperbole, but you get what I’m saying). Don’t look at the decisions that make up your life like you’re a spectator watching from the outside of the house. You are in the house! You are the house!

Smart is something you can do. You can study, you can read, you can digest information. I’ve been “smart.” If there’s one thing Caribbean people will praise it’s a “smart child,” so I always knew that by someone’s standards I was smart. But I can tell you as a 30-something year-old balancing work, motherhood, life responsibilities, personal goals, relationships, et al, being smart is of little to no help!!!! I find myself instead needing wisdom. What would a wise person do? But wise is something you have to be. It happens spontaneously and often without your knowing. I can’t download wisdom — UNFORTUNATELY I HAVE TRIED. Self-help books only get you part of the way. The only way to be wise is to live, and keep living. Living with an openness that lets the wisdom sink in until one day you find that it takes you less time to know what to do and how to respond to things, but mostly you’ll notice you just know how to be.

A few words on being a gym bro now: *ahem*
I have always hated working out. It felt like a necessary evil put upon me for being over a size 10. And I didn’t even mind being over a size 10 all that much anyway! So I’ve always had an-up-and-down relationship with it. But lately and under much duress, I’ve resorted to going to the gym daily as a way to break up the accumulated stress, fear, anger I’ve absorbed into my body. And in doing so, I realized something — the something I’m sharing with you now: working out is the same as popping bubble wrap. When I was little my mom would give me bubble wrap to pop while we watched TV. It was something to do with our hands (because Caribbean women always have to be do something with their hands. Any rest at all made you slack.) and as a kid, the popping sound was exciting. But more than that was the way it felt. Pressing down each bubble of captured air, adjusting the tension until it popped. It felt like control. The build up of the tension, the satisfaction of the release (I’m so sorry I know that sounds sexual. I don’t mean it that way!!!!! 😭). Sometimes I would get creative and pop a pattern. Other times I would twist it like I was wringing a towel dry to get a rapid succession of squishy pop-pop-pops. And if I knew that doing 4 sets of 12 donkey kicks felt like that, I would’ve done it much sooner.

Breastmilk, you made my dayyyy 🥛 and I mean this very literally because my latest for @essence magazine is out ahead of National Breastfeeding Month. I’ve found myself talking about pregnancy and motherhood a lot lately (a natural evolution), but breastfeeding has always been a tough spot for me because *drumroll please*🥁 I never quite understood it, even after having a child and struggling with it myself, I was never able to put the puzzle together of WHY (hint hint: as with much in this country, it’s a systemic lack of care for Black women/folks! Who knew?!) until I researched, interviewed and wrote this piece. And a special thank you to my editor @ghostwritervic and to @bycourtneydanielle and @mswrightsway for sharing your intimate stories with me for this piece!

I used to work with a woman who told me she would drive around (pre-Google maps, post-Map Quest print outs) and get lost on purpose. Just so she could figure out how to get where she was going in new ways, on back roads. Or to get to new places in unknown ways. Lost on purpose! Ha! I thought she was crazy. I get it now. Getting lost is scary, but it IS an opportunity. It IS a way to evolve. When you are lost, it IS the best time to be found. 📍 You are here. How will you get lost?

Every time I visit New York, I find pieces of myself I forgot. Summer 2006 (or 2007 I can’t remember tbh) I went to Guyana for the first and, so far, last time. It was a place I’d heard about my entire life, a place that shaped my life. Summer before last I learned that biologically, I’m not actually Guyanese (a whole other tale) but it feels wrong to not claim myself as a roti-and-curry, bake-and-salt fish, mango-and-guinep, land-of-many-waters gyal. It’s in how I talk, how I cook, how I whine, how I laugh, how I live. Anyway, here’s to meeting and remeeting ourselves. 🇬🇾 🥭

I have spent the better part of this year crying. Crying in the shower, in the gym, on the floor, in the car, standing in front of the fridge looking for something to distract me from the fact that I am, yet again, crying. But as sure as they they fall, the tears stop, the sun rises, music plays, my daughter laughs, friends call, YOU GET TO SEE BEYONCÉ WITH YOUR FRIENDS OF OVER 15 YEARS!!!!!!! and life starts again. Life starts again. YOU start again. We are resilient and beautiful and we are part of it all, baby, and there is room for it all within us. Obviously, I would like to be happy all the time, but I think it’s more true to say I want to be full. I want a full and fully felt life. And if that means crying at the fridge one night and singing ALIEN SUPERSTAR in a crowd of thousands of people who have also cried, yelled and felt lost on another, then okay. I own that and it’s mine.

The most powerful thing you can do in this life is make yourself. Again and again, as many times as you need to and in as many ways as feel true. You are your best thing, and oftentimes you might end up being your only thing. Pour yourself into the making of you because it will be the spring from which all else flows.

Thique, thick, thicc, whatever you call it, was a well-intentioned yet misdirected way to get Anglosaxon America to be comfortable with the fact that most people (women and femmes especially) are not and never will be a single-digit size. And not to be all “black ppl started it” but like, the appreciation certainly started there. Anyway, all of this is coming about because I cut my hair (duh, I WILL be talking about it for at least a month — okay two, can you tell I used to have a blog) and being a woman of certain size (just say fat!) having short hair was the SCARIEST THING I COULD EVER DO 😱 because “what will I hide behind?  Don’t you know having long hair automatically makes you a size smaller?!” But after a full fiscal quarter of regular exercise, gains in mobility, strength and flexibility *drumroll* I still look the way I do. And 15 year old me would’ve NEVER thought I could do any of this, much less enjoy it — without the reward of getting smaller. But I do! And this may very well be how I always look. Short hair, long hair, dresses or jeans, imma look like this!!!! And by George, I am so very happy to be happy with that. P.S. Tyler Perry is a menace! 😂If he was able to buy BET from Paramount he would’ve been too powerful.

Try it today!

I have SO MANY THOUGHTS AND FEELINGS about this BUT the gist is that even at our highest, most accomplished and newsworthy, if there’s even a little bit of room to chip away at a Black woman’s moment, someone is going to try to. Let me repeat, I am not against Taylor Swift, she is amazing and accomplished! But this headline didn’t need her name mentioned. In the article for context? Sure. Hell, even in the dek! But the fact that Beyoncé had to share the exclusive announcement with someone else, specifically the mention of her deal “following” someone else’s IN THE HEADLINE — @parkwood @beyonce momma Tina @mstinaknowles — someone, give @variety a call. That’s shitty journalism with a headline that needs to be edited for clarity, thank you. Context goes in the article. The big news is that #renaissanceworldtour is gonna be in AMC theaters, full stop, period. #rwt #whydidawhitemanwritethisanyway #beyhive do your thing lol

After a year that threatened to take me from myself, how lucky am I to have a reminder of who I’ve been and who I come from? The people, places, things integral to the making of a person. Nothing can take you from yourself when you know what makes you up. This is the recipe. As long as I have the recipe, I have me.

I didn’t do much outside of survive and move cross country this summer, but I did get to do a few fun things with my friends and it is a badge of honor that I got to see thee @victoriamonet 7-time Grammy nominated artist (okay!) with my bestie in one of my favorite cities. And she better sweep, you hear me?! Also, I kept the awkward audio in because I wish people knew how calculated these cute lil’ influencer video are. The amount of times I’ve heard “does it look good?” shooting for myself and for my friends 😂 no one and nothing is as cool as it looks.

Today I took a window break. This is a 5-minute-or-so pause where I look out the window, breathe, appreciate the beauty of the fall trees and try to remind myself I have much to be grateful for. I do (given the state of the world, I do).

My breath slowed, my jaw relaxed and I heard the familiar song, “look at how much you have to be grateful for.” I closed my eyes and nodded in agreement. “Yes, so much.” Satisfied with my gratitude, I inhaled for 3, exhaled for 3 one last time. When I opened my eyes, I was pissed. 

For the first time since I discovered gratitude as a way to ground myself, I got the feeling that being grateful was not a fulfilling alternative or solution to that lingering sense of “something ain’t right.”

Being grateful does not make bad things good or wrong things right. It does not solve, it subdues. It’s true. SOMETHING ISN’T RIGHT. Am I equipped to fix it yet? No. But I know all the gratitude in the world isn’t going to. I want to hear what my anger and frustration are telling me. I don’t want to wellness it away. And the truth is, gratitude and anger feel like they can coexist. I’ll let you know when I figure out how.

Ahead of the holidays, I just want to remind you all of two things: 1) you don’t have to do everything. In fact, take one thing off your plate, purposefully, every day. Celebrate the thing you did not do. 2) Being hot™ is a valid form of self-care and acting like it’s not (aka denying yourself the personal satisfaction of seeing yourself as hot™ for the comfort of others) is just prolonging your liberation. I encourage you all to be as hot as possible while enjoying whatever festivities you partake in! 💕 Love you!

Life is hard. By design, this life is hard. It was never meant to be easy for us.  But I’m telling you—no, begging you: don’t get stuck waiting to survive. I hope you try. I hope that you try and you survive in a way that exists outside of how you were intended and expected to.

There is wonder-full weight to motherhood. It wears like a second skin, the responsibility of it. Everything they experience from the moment they’re given to you—their comfort & discomfort, joy & sadness, laughter & cries—becomes yours, too. Feeling that all so suddenly (the moment you meet them, it hits you) terrified me. And I was one of the lucky ones. 

For Giving Tuesday, I want to spotlight @tender, a non-profit here in Atlanta helping bridge the gap for moms who need help carrying the weight of motherhood under systemically unfair conditions.

Even with every heavy thing I felt as a new mother, I  never had to wonder if I’d have enough diapers for her, formula to feed her with or money for rent to keep a roof over our heads. I don’t know what I would’ve done if I’d I had to. Because of that, I give and invite you to, too. $25 is enough to provide a family with diapers for a week (I’ve volunteered at their diaper bank — it makes a difference.) ♥️ Link in bio to donate.

This year was the angriest year of my life. Just seismic wave after wave of anger. I accomplished levels of anger so powerful they dislodged decades-old angers from where they had settled and left me wondering what to do with the fragments of a girl, now a woman, who could not be angry for herself. So I did what I always do when I’m given something that shakes me: I wrote. 

For the January/February 2024 issue of @essence, here’s “You Mad?” Writing this article, I learned that anger rarely ever visits alone. It comes holding hands with disappointment, fear, embarassment, sadness. It comes cloaking grief. Digging through our collective anger, I found context for my own (a lot of it grief). 

I’m grateful @ghostwritervic let this run in the first issue of the year because my hope is that as you’re making your New Year’s resolutions, you make room for anger. I know many of us are yearning for the #softlife or strive to be unbothered, but let’s just call it: this world is rife with botheration. It’s around every corner. For Black girls, now women, especially. 

At its best, being unbothered is a solution that gives you room to just keep going, to get through to the other side. And if you make it your only recourse against the things that bother you, you’ll find they’ll come back hydra-headed and angrier than you left them. For 2024, let your anger speak to you, sit with it, question it (read the article for how to do that in a safe and healthy way lol) and see how it reveals a truer version of yourself.

Getting free, as difficult as it was, as much as it took of you, will only be the beginning. Once you get your freedom (one of many times you will have to; there is so much to be free of), the work of finding out what to do with it begins. What will you do now that you are free? [a smattering of things coaxing me through the never ending “what next?” of it all]

Unfortunately for me, a true yapper (girls who always got in trouble for talking in class stand up 📣 ), it would seem that sometimes you do need to shut the hell up & sit the hell down in order to hear yourself think. This is not me doing that, clearly, but I’m admitting that I accept this. And that I will be shutting up more in the hopes of giving what really needs to be said room to take root.

a weird, warm, writerly woman
